            <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <h3>What does a stock correlation of 1.0 mean?</h3>
                <p>A correlation of 1.0 means perfect positive correlation. It indicates that two assets move in the exact same direction, in perfect proportion. This is typically only seen when comparing an asset to itself, or to an ETF that strictly tracks it.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <h3>Why is negative correlation important for a portfolio?</h3>
                <p>Negative correlation (values between 0 and -1) means that when one asset goes up, the other tends to go down. Holding negatively correlated assets can reduce overall portfolio volatility and mitigate losses during market downturns, a core principle of modern portfolio theory.</p>
            </div>
